textDisplay:
I'm calling Food Network and Good Eats on this one. Suggesting using a stainless steel mixing bowl to pop corn is a bad idea.


I tried it and the direct heat and flame discolored a perfectly good stainless steel mixing bowl. Thanks for nothing Food Network and Good Eats!


Not to mention that it's a bit dangerous trying to Jiffy Pop using a bowl with an unstable round bottom and without a proper handle on it. That bowl gets hot awful quick. Food Network, this is a lawsuit waiting to happen!



Use a pot with a heavy bottom or a wok, if you have one, or buy a proper popcorn popper instead of trying to use a thin walled stainless mixing bowl for something for which it was not designed. Use the right tool for the right job. Don't ruin your nice, shiny metal mixing bowls just for the sake of popping corn.

textDisplay:
I've been using a round bottom wok for years (on a gas stove). It worked great!

But now I don't have a gas stove, but have a smooth top electric stove. The wok doesn't work there, because there isn't enough contact between the wok and the stovetop. So .... I turn a wooden barstool sideways. Rest the wok on the (now) horizontal legs. Then put a heat gun under it. And I'm back to cooking popcorn in my wok!
textOriginal:
I've been using a round bottom wok for years (on a gas stove).  It worked great!

But now I don't have a gas stove, but have a smooth top electric stove.  The wok doesn't work there, because there isn't enough contact between the wok and the stovetop.  So .... I turn a wooden barstool sideways.  Rest the wok on the (now) horizontal legs.  Then put a heat gun under it.  And I'm back to cooking popcorn in my wok!

textDisplay:
@Andy Fletcher Its actually better not to clarify the butter, but just reduce it. Just don't cook the popcorn in the butter (since that will burn the milk solids). Just reduce the butter over medium-low heat until it stops foaming, then toss your popcorn in it as is.

The enemy here is not milk solids; they carry a lot of the flavor of butter. The enemy is water content.

You can even kill two birds with one stone here by dissolving your salt (and other flavorings) in like 1/4th of a cup of water, and adding that to the butter as your reduce it. The dissolved salt/solutes will precipitate out of the water and into the oil with a much finer granularity, since they do not have time to form larger bodies as the water evaporates.

Powdering the salt and other flavorants is mostly useful if you do not want to use a lot of oil.

The dissolved salt/solutes will precipitate out of the water and into the oil with a much finer granularity, since they do not have time to form larger bodies as the water evaporates.

textDisplay: @robinsss if you use a reasonable vessel instead of wok or a bowl, you really don't have to either. The best vessel is either an 'air popper' or one of those movie theater poppers since the popped corn is immediately remove from the heat source. Alternatively, a tall narrow sauce pan works pretty well too. As the popcorn pops, it moves farther up the column of the saucepan, and cannot get underneath the kernels.. The smaller the bottom of the saucepan, the less popcorn will touch it. The taller the saucepan, the farther away from the heat source that the popped kernels can move without overflowing.

textDisplay:
if you heat butter to the temp that popcorn pops at best (about medium-high) you will scorch the butter and it will taste like motor oil. If you cook it at a temp that won't scorch the butter, the popcorn doesn't pop completely, and it ends up chewy.

If you want to flavor it with butter, reduce the butter in a seperate saucepan on medium-low until it stops foaming, and just toss the popcorn in that after it's done. Just use a smaller amount of oil to pop it. It will pop completely dry, but it doesn't heat the kernels evenly when dry, and ends up burning part of the hull before it pops.

if you heat butter to the temp that popcorn pops at best (about medium-high) you will scorch the butter and it will taste like motor oil. If you cook it at a temp that won't scorch the butter, the popcorn doesn't pop completely, and it ends up chewy.

If you want to flavor it with butter, reduce the butter in a seperate saucepan on medium-low until it stops foaming, and just toss the popcorn in that after it's done.  Just use a smaller amount of oil to pop it. It will pop completely dry, but it doesn't heat the kernels evenly when dry, and ends up burning part of the hull before it pops.

textDisplay:
@Michelle Hasty it would. the main point of the bowl is to serve the popcorn in the vessel you cooked it in; one without a giant handle, that doesn't take very long to cool down. the part about the shape of the bowl helping the cooking process is patently wrong. A standard saucepan achieves what the bowl is supposed to better than the bowl does.

A wok/bowl is good for stir fry because there is a heat gradient, so only a small part of the contents are exposed to high temperature at a time. However, most things you cook in a wok are moist, so the moisture of the ingredients cool the higher up parts of the surface of the wok to a non-scorching temperature. Popcorn doesn't do this. So it can be scorched even by higher parts of the wok's surface.

The popcorn naturally fractionates because the popped kernels cannot move underneath the denser unpopped kernels. The gradient of heat on the bottom of a wok actually ensures that a lot of the popcorn is exposed to scorching heat longer than it needs to be, and the 'wider at the top' shape of a bowl/wok ensures that more of the popcorn is lower in the vessel, which is exactly the opposite of what you want.

He recently re-did this method for a youtube video and burned a lot of the popcorn doing it.

textDisplay: This recipe is fake and doesn’t work. You’ll get slimy eggs every time guaranteed. At 2:07 he’s pulling an egg out of the water that is uncooked and disintegrating but the scene cuts and he magically has a solid poached egg that looks completely different. And just we are clear, vinegar breaks down protein which tenderizes meat. When you add vinegar to the water it makes the egg proteins disintegrate which is what holds the egg together.
